    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-07-19T03:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-07-19T03:30:00-05:00" n="321"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d321">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">330/7–1950: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-07-19T14:00:00+05:30"
                            >July 19, 1950—2 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 19—8:12 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>147. 1. Bajpai informs me not possible effect release messages so early as 9:30
                    July 19 Washington time because Nehru wishes his reply to Secretary’s message to
                    be delivered by Mme. Pandit today to be incorporated in release. Furthermore
                    Moscow must be informed.</p>
                <p>2. <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> is anxious that messages be published in
                    New Delhi papers July 20 and therefore is informing both Washington and Moscow
                    its intention issue release its exchanges with Washington and Moscow not
                    including Nehru’s message of July 17, July 20, 3 a. m. Delhi time. I assume this
                    permits sufficient time to elapse after statement contemplated by President
                    (Deptel 88, July 18).</p>
                <p>3. Fearing that there may be some delay in receipt reply by Mme. Pandit, Bajpai
                    gave me copy to transmit direct Department. If Mme. Pandit’s text not received
                    before time scheduled for release Department might arrange with her approval
                    publication text given me which is contained in <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 148.<note n="1" xml:id="d321fn1">Received at 9:27 a. m. on
                        July 19, <ref target="#pg_425">p. 425</ref>. The Department of State
                        released the texts of the Nehru–Acheson exchanges on July 19 at 3:30 p. m.
                            (<gloss target="#t_EDT1">EDT</gloss>); for texts, see the Department of
                        State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 19, 1950, p. 170.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
